    <DatePublished>2010-01-01T00:00:00</DatePublished>
    <Summary>{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\f0\fs17 You will see that the link for the above 'pdf-test.pdf' works on your machine even though the program uses absolute filepaths and I attached it using my filesystem.\par
This is because the program also does a check for a valid relative filepath after checking for the absolute filepath.\par
To work, the PDF file must be located WITHIN the project directory, and the same relative directories as when it was added.\par
This means if I want to add 'pdf-test.pdf' from D:\\example\\PDF-file and access it on a different machine, I must first copy it to D:\\filler\\text\\ProgrammingAssignment4\\ProgrammingAssignment4\\...\par
The program uses the absolute filepath, but chops off everything before the project directory and concatenates it with the parent directory of the programs running directory\par
(i.e. ...ProgrammingAssignment4)\par
I.e.:\par
The PDF file relative directory = "...\\somedirectory\\pdf-test.pdf"\par
The Environment.CurrentDirectory (minus \\bin\\...) = "\\absolute\\path\\to\\ProgrammingAssignment4\\ProgrammingAssignment4..."\par
The used directory = ""\\absolute\\path\\to\\ProgrammingAssignment4\\ProgrammingAssignment4\\somedirectory\\pdf-test.pdf"\par
\par
(.rlist) files with attached PDFs can be opened on other machines, but the attached PDFs must be within the project directory under the same relative filepath\par
More in the block comment within linklabel2_linkClicked in ReportLIst.cs (the event handler that uses the filepaths)\par
}
